    <p class="text-gray-300">It remains to compute the action of  <span class="math">\\pi</span>  on the basis of  <span class="math">J[\\ell]</span> , without computing dense polynomials of linear degree. To do this one uses a iterative square-and-multiply modulo  <span class="math">\\ell J</span> . This is done by finding some set of functions vanishing on  <span class="math">J[\\ell]</span> , and reducing all intermediate results modulo these functions. For the  <span class="math">g = 1</span>  case, these are the multivariate division polynomials  <span class="math">\\psi_{\\ell}</span> , with  <span class="math">d = \\deg(\\psi_{\\ell}) = O(\\ell^2)</span> . Following Elkies, for  <span class="math">\\sim 1/2</span>  of all primes one can instead work modulo a polynomial of degree  <span class="math">d = O(\\ell)</span>  which reduces the asymptotic complexity substantially. For  <span class="math">g &amp;gt; 1</span> , Cantor gives analogous polynomials for the Mumford form [13], and Abelard [1] proves that these polynomials have degree  <span class="math">d = O_g(\\ell^3)</span>  in general, and  <span class="math">d = O(\\ell^2)</span>  for  <span class="math">g = 3</span> . This allows the complexity to be effectively bounded. Abelard also shows that for curves with real multiplication, the degree is reduced to  <span class="math">d = O(\\ell^{3/g})</span> .</p>

